				<description>&lt;p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;img class=&#34;img-fluid &#34;&#xA;            src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-2800x1575.png&#34;&#xA;             srcset=&#34;http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-576x324.webp 576w, http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-768x432.webp 768w, http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-992x558.webp 992w, http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-1200x675.webp 1200w, http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-1400x787.webp 1400w, http://localhost:1313/blog/blog/img/06GettyImages-829469540-1152x648-2800x1575.webp 2800w&#34; sizes=&#34;100vw&#34; height=&#34;1575&#34; width=&#34;2800&#34; alt=&#34;Featured Image&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction-to-maggot-therapy&#34; class=&#34;heading &#34;&gt;Introduction to Maggot Therapy&lt;a href=&#34;#introduction-to-maggot-therapy&#34; aria-labelledby=&#34;introduction-to-maggot-therapy&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;!-- &lt;i class=&#34;fas fa-link anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; --&gt;&#xA;        &lt;svg class=&#34;svg-inline--fa fas fa-link anchor&#34; fill=&#34;currentColor&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; role=&#34;img&#34; viewBox=&#34;0 0 576 512&#34;&gt;&lt;use href=&#34;#fas-link&#34;&gt;&lt;/use&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&amp;nbsp;&#xA;    &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Maggot therapy, also known as maggot debridement therapy (MDT), is a type of biotherapy that involves the use of live maggots to clean and heal wounds. The concept of maggot therapy has been around for centuries, with reports of its use dating back to the American Civil War. Despite its long history, maggot therapy has only recently gained popularity as a treatment option for chronic wounds, such as diabetic foot ulcers and venous leg ulcers.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
